<subSubSection id="C35C654DFF81232DFE36FD25FE7D9BFE" pageId="4" pageNumber="224" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph id="8BF936C6FF81232DFE36FD25FD8F9A8A" blockId="4.[386,535,670,694]" box="[386,535,670,694]" pageId="4" pageNumber="224">
<heading id="D0B181AAFF81232DFE36FD25FD8F9A8A" bold="true" box="[386,535,670,694]" centered="true" fontSize="10" level="2" pageId="4" pageNumber="224" reason="2">
<taxonomicName id="4C464D45FF81232DFE36FD25FD8F9A8A" authorityName="Nalepa" authorityYear="1898" box="[386,535,670,694]" class="Arachnida" family="Eriophyidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="4" pageNumber="224" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">
<emphasis id="B932EAD4FF81232DFE36FD25FD8F9A8A" bold="true" box="[386,535,670,694]" pageId="4" pageNumber="224">Eriophyidae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF936C6FF81232DFF2BFD63FE7D9BFE" blockId="4.[159,762,728,1949]" pageId="4" pageNumber="224">
Thirteen species of 
<taxonomicName id="4C464D45FF81232DFECBFD63FD889ACC" authorityName="Nalepa" authorityYear="1898" box="[383,528,728,752]" class="Arachnida" family="Eriophyidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="4" pageNumber="224" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Eriophyidae</taxonomicName>
have been recorded on citrus in the world (
<bibRefCitation id="EFD74B37FF81232DFE75FD40FD6E9B2F" author="Amrine J. W. Jr. &amp; Stasny T. A." box="[449,758,763,787]" pageId="4" pageNumber="224" refId="ref10520" refString="Amrine J. W. Jr., Stasny T. A. 1994 - Catalog of the Eriophyoidea (Acarina: Prostigmata) of the World - Michigan: Indira Publishing House. pp. 798." type="book" year="1994">Amrine and Stasny, 1994</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFD74B37FF81232DFF2BFCA5FE549B0A" author="Childers C. C. &amp; Achor D. S." box="[159,460,798,822]" pageId="4" pageNumber="224" pagination="79 - 87" refId="ref11548" refString="Childers C. C., Achor D. S. 1999 - The eriophyoid mite complex on Florida citrus (Acari: Eriophyidae and Diptilomiopidae) - Proc. Fla. State Hortic. Soc., 112: 79 - 87." type="journal article" year="1999">Childers and Achor, 1999</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFD74B37FF81232DFE6CFCA5FDEB9B0A" author="Gerson U." box="[472,627,798,822]" pageId="4" pageNumber="224" pagination="3 - 12" refId="ref12727" refString="Gerson U. 2003 - Acarine pests of citrus: overview and non chemical control - Systematic &amp; Applied Acarology, 8: 3 - 12." type="journal article" year="2003">Gerson, 2003</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFD74B37FF81232DFDCAFCA5FF669B65" author="Dhooria M. S. &amp; Bhullar M. B. &amp; Mallik B." pageId="4" pageNumber="224" refId="ref12091" refString="Dhooria M. S., Bhullar M. B., Mallik B. 2005 - Mite pests of citrus and their management in India, AINP (Agricultural Acarology) - Bangalore: UAS. pp. 28." type="book" year="2005">
Dhooria 
<emphasis id="B932EAD4FF81232DFD52FCA4FF2A9B65" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="224">et al</emphasis>
., 2005
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFD74B37FF81232DFEBDFCFAFE319B65" author="Vacante V." box="[265,425,833,857]" pageId="4" pageNumber="224" refId="ref17129" refString="Vacante V. 2010 - Citrus Mites - Wallingford: CABI Publishing. pp. 378." type="book" year="2010">Vacante, 2010</bibRefCitation>
) (
<tableCitation id="C6C4037DFF81232DFE0AFCFAFD8A9B65" box="[446,530,833,857]" captionStart="TABLE" captionStartId="3.[159,172,308,327]" captionText="TABLE 1: Mites of the family Eriophyidae Nalepa collected on citrus in the world. Following Gerson (2003) the pest status is indicated as Ma (major), Me (medium), Mi (minor), and U (unknown). For references see Vacante (2010)." pageId="4" pageNumber="224">Table 1</tableCitation>
). Of these, only the citrus bud mite, 
<taxonomicName id="4C464D45FF81232DFEEFFCDFFE4B9B40" baseAuthorityName="Ewing" baseAuthorityYear="1937" box="[347,467,868,892]" class="Arachnida" family="Eriophyidae" genus="Aceria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="4" pageNumber="224" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sheldoni">
<emphasis id="B932EAD4FF81232DFEEFFCDFFE4B9B40" box="[347,467,868,892]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="224">A. sheldoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the pink citrus rust mite, 
<taxonomicName id="4C464D45FF81232DFF2BFC3CFE5C9BA3" authority="(Keifer)" baseAuthorityName="Keifer" box="[159,452,903,927]" class="Arachnida" family="Eriophyidae" genus="Aculops" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="4" pageNumber="224" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pelekassi">
<emphasis id="B932EAD4FF81232DFF2BFC3CFEC69BA3" box="[159,350,903,927]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="224">Aculops pelekassi</emphasis>
(Keifer)
</taxonomicName>
, and the citrus rust mite, 
<taxonomicName id="4C464D45FF81232DFF2BFC11FE879BFE" baseAuthorityName="Ashmead" baseAuthorityYear="1879" box="[159,287,938,962]" class="Arachnida" family="Eriophyidae" genus="Phyllocoptruta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="4" pageNumber="224" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="oleivora">
<emphasis id="B932EAD4FF81232DFF2BFC11FE879BFE" box="[159,287,938,962]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="224">Ph. oleivora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, are major pests.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C35C654DFF81232DFF71FC6CFF459D72" pageId="4" pageNumber="224" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BF936C6FF81232DFF71FC6CFF459D72" blockId="4.[159,762,728,1949]" pageId="4" pageNumber="224">
The species responsible of minor damage are the brown citrus rust mite, 
<taxonomicName id="4C464D45FF81232DFE77FC41FD6E9C2E" authority="Keifer" authorityName="Keifer" box="[451,758,1018,1042]" class="Arachnida" family="Eriophyidae" genus="Tegolophus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="4" pageNumber="224" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="australis">
<emphasis id="B932EAD4FF81232DFE77FC41FD3A9C2E" box="[451,674,1018,1042]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="224">Tegolophus australis</emphasis>
Keifer
</taxonomicName>
, the new brown citrus rust mite, 
<taxonomicName id="4C464D45FF81232DFDAAFBA5FF7D9C64" authority="Flechtmann" authorityName="Flechtmann" class="Arachnida" family="Eriophyidae" genus="Tegolophus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="4" pageNumber="224" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brunneus">
<emphasis id="B932EAD4FF81232DFDAAFBA5FD399C09" box="[542,673,1053,1077]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="224">T. brunneus</emphasis>
Flechtmann
</taxonomicName>
, and the citrus grey mite or citrus blotch mite, 
<taxonomicName id="4C464D45FF81232DFF5EFBD8FDC49C47" authority="Keifer. The" authorityName="Keifer. The" box="[234,604,1123,1147]" class="Arachnida" family="Eriophyidae" genus="Calacarus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="4" pageNumber="224" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="citrifolii">
<emphasis id="B932EAD4FF81232DFF5EFBD8FE209C47" box="[234,440,1123,1147]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="224">Calacarus citrifolii</emphasis>
Keifer. The
</taxonomicName>
other seven species have no known pest status. In addition, a few rare vagrant species (
<taxonomicName id="4C464D45FF81232DFE60FB12FDEB9CFD" box="[468,627,1193,1217]" class="Arachnida" family="Eriophyidae" genus="Acaricalus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Prostigmata" pageId="4" pageNumber="224" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis id="B932EAD4FF81232DFE60FB12FDDF9CFD" box="[468,583,1193,1217]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="224">Acaricalus</emphasis>
sp.
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C464D45FF81232DFD36FB12FF5A9CD8" class="Arachnida" family="Eriophyidae" genus="Tegolophus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="4" pageNumber="224" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis id="B932EAD4FF81232DFD36FB12FD629CFD" box="[642,762,1193,1217]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="224">Tegolophus</emphasis>
sp.
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C464D45FF81232DFF66FB76FEFA9CD9" box="[210,354,1229,1253]" class="Arachnida" family="Eriophyidae" genus="Abacarus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="4" pageNumber="224" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis id="B932EAD4FF81232DFF66FB76FEAF9CD9" box="[210,311,1229,1253]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="224">Abacarus</emphasis>
sp.
</taxonomicName>
) were found on citrus in 
<collectingRegion id="4982F824FF81232DFD11FB76FD629CD9" box="[677,762,1229,1253]" country="Uruguay" name="Florida" pageId="4" pageNumber="224">Florida</collectingRegion>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFD74B37FF81232DFF13FB4BFE429D34" author="Childers C. C. &amp; Achor D. S." box="[167,474,1264,1288]" pageId="4" pageNumber="224" pagination="79 - 87" refId="ref11548" refString="Childers C. C., Achor D. S. 1999 - The eriophyoid mite complex on Florida citrus (Acari: Eriophyidae and Diptilomiopidae) - Proc. Fla. State Hortic. Soc., 112: 79 - 87." type="journal article" year="1999">Childers and Achor, 1999</bibRefCitation>
), but their pest status is unknown and they are not been treated in this review.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C35C654DFF81232DFF71FAD9FBF89B22" pageId="4" pageNumber="224" type="reference_group">
<paragraph id="8BF936C6FF81232DFF71FAD9FEB79E71" blockId="4.[159,762,728,1949]" pageId="4" pageNumber="224">
<taxonomicName id="4C464D45FF81232DFF71FAD9FE749D46" baseAuthorityName="Ashmead" baseAuthorityYear="1879" box="[197,492,1378,1402]" class="Arachnida" family="Eriophyidae" genus="Phyllocoptruta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="4" pageNumber="224" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="oleivora">
<emphasis id="B932EAD4FF81232DFF71FAD9FE749D46" bold="true" box="[197,492,1378,1402]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="224">Phyllocoptruta oleivora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a tropical species, with worldwide distribution. It is a rust mites, injurious to leaves, twigs and citrus fruits. Optimum temperature for development is between 30 and 32째C (
<bibRefCitation id="EFD74B37FF81232DFF5CFA54FE0E9E3B" author="Ebrahim H. M." box="[232,406,1519,1543]" pageId="4" pageNumber="224" pagination="143 - 161" refId="ref12307" refString="Ebrahim H. M. 2000 - Influence of temperature and relative humidity on the biology and life table parameters of Phyllocoptruta oleivora and Aculops pelekassi (Acari: Eriophyidae) on &quot; Hamlin &quot; orange in Central Florida - Egypt. J. Agric. Res., 78: 143 - 161." type="journal article" year="2000">Ebrahim, 2000</bibRefCitation>
) and it develops well at high RH values and particularly after rain (
<bibRefCitation id="EFD74B37FF81232DFDC6F9A9FD6E9E16" author="Pratt R. M." box="[626,758,1554,1578]" pageId="4" pageNumber="224" pagination="48 - 51" refId="ref15872" refString="Pratt R. M. 1957 - Relation between moisture conditions and rust mite infestations - Proc. Fla. State Hortic. Soc., 70: 48 - 51." type="journal article" year="1957">Pratt, 1957</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFD74B37FF81232DFF2BF98DFEBB9E71" author="Dean H. A." box="[159,291,1589,1613]" pageId="4" pageNumber="224" pagination="228 - 232" refId="ref11997" refString="Dean H. A. 1959 - Seasonal distribution of mites on Texas grapefruit - J. Econ. Entomol., 52: 228 - 232." type="journal article" year="1959">Dean, 1959</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF936C6FF81232DFF71F9D9FDCE9F16" blockId="4.[159,762,728,1949]" pageId="4" pageNumber="224">
<taxonomicName id="4C464D45FF81232DFF71F9D9FE309E46" box="[197,424,1634,1658]" class="Arachnida" family="Eriophyidae" genus="Aculops" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="4" pageNumber="224" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pelekassi">
<emphasis id="B932EAD4FF81232DFF71F9D9FE309E46" bold="true" box="[197,424,1634,1658]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="224">Aculops pelekassi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a subtropical species recorded in the Palearctic, 
<collectingRegion id="4982F824FF81232DFE60F93EFDAD9EA1" box="[468,565,1669,1693]" country="Morocco" name="Oriental" pageId="4" pageNumber="224">Oriental</collectingRegion>
and Neotropical regions. It is a rust mite, injurious to leaves, twigs and citrus fruits and its optimum conditions for development are temperatures between 22 and 27째C and 75 to 77% of RH (
<bibRefCitation id="EFD74B37FF81232DFE29F8AAFDD39F16" author="Ebrahim H. M." box="[413,587,1809,1834]" pageId="4" pageNumber="224" pagination="143 - 161" refId="ref12307" refString="Ebrahim H. M. 2000 - Influence of temperature and relative humidity on the biology and life table parameters of Phyllocoptruta oleivora and Aculops pelekassi (Acari: Eriophyidae) on &quot; Hamlin &quot; orange in Central Florida - Egypt. J. Agric. Res., 78: 143 - 161." type="journal article" year="2000">Ebrahim, 2000</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF936C6FF81232DFF71F885FC589AB7" blockId="4.[159,762,728,1949]" lastBlockId="4.[826,1429,311,1948]" pageId="4" pageNumber="224">
<taxonomicName id="4C464D45FF81232DFF71F885FEE39F6A" baseAuthorityName="Ewing" baseAuthorityYear="1937" box="[197,379,1854,1878]" class="Arachnida" family="Eriophyidae" genus="Aceria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="4" pageNumber="224" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sheldoni">
<emphasis id="B932EAD4FF81232DFF71F885FEE39F6A" bold="true" box="[197,379,1854,1878]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="224">Aceria sheldoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has worldwide distribution; it is adapted to humid conditions, pertaining in coastal citrus groves. Optimal egg hatching is at 25째C and 98% RH but it is much lower under dry conditions (such as 35-40% RH). Population survival declines rapidly (50% dying within 30 minutes) at extreme low RH values and temperatures of 30 and -15째C (
<bibRefCitation id="EFD74B37FF81232DFCF6FE78FC6399E7" author="Sternlicht M." box="[834,1019,451,475]" pageId="4" pageNumber="224" pagination="221 - 230" refId="ref16863" refString="Sternlicht M. 1970 - Contribution to the biology of the citrus bud mite Aceria sheldoni (Ewing) (Acarina: Eriophyidae) - Ann. Appl. Biol., 65: 221 - 230." type="journal article" year="1970">Sternlicht, 1970</bibRefCitation>
). The ecological role (and the phytopathological importance) of the citrus bud mite is unclear. The mite is probably a symbiont of the lemon, adjusting the flowering of the host plant that offers protection and nutritional resources (
<bibRefCitation id="EFD74B37FF81232DFA83FDF4FC2D9AB7" author="Vacante V. &amp; Bonsignore C. &amp; Federico S." pageId="4" pageNumber="224" pagination="103 - 105" refId="ref17146" refString="Vacante V., Bonsignore C., Federico S. 2007 - Indagini sul ruolo ecologico di Aceria sheldoni su limone - Italus Hortus, 14: 103 - 105." type="journal article" year="2007">
Vacante 
<emphasis id="B932EAD4FF81232DFC8EFDC8FCFF9AB6" box="[826,871,626,650]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="224">et al</emphasis>
., 2007
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF936C6FF81232DFCD4FD27FBF89B22" blockId="4.[826,1429,311,1948]" pageId="4" pageNumber="224">
<taxonomicName id="4C464D45FF81232DFCD4FD27FBF89A88" box="[864,1120,668,692]" class="Arachnida" family="Eriophyidae" genus="Tegolophus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="4" pageNumber="224" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="australis">
<emphasis id="B932EAD4FF81232DFCD4FD27FBF89A88" bold="true" box="[864,1120,668,692]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="224">Tegolophus australis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a rust mite and its geographical distribution interests only the Australasian region, where apparently it does not cause serious damage to citrus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C35C654DFF81232CFCD4FC8BFDAA9A1D" lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="225" pageId="4" pageNumber="224" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BF936C6FF81232DFCD4FC8BFC629BB2" blockId="4.[826,1429,311,1948]" pageId="4" pageNumber="224">
<taxonomicName id="4C464D45FF81232DFCD4FC8BFBFF9B74" box="[864,1127,816,840]" class="Arachnida" family="Eriophyidae" genus="Tegolophus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="4" pageNumber="224" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brunneus">
<emphasis id="B932EAD4FF81232DFCD4FC8BFBFF9B74" bold="true" box="[864,1127,816,840]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="224">Tegolophus brunneus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a rust mite with Neotropical distribution and does not represent any danger to citrus.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF936C6FF81232DFCD4FC1BFB2E9D2B" blockId="4.[826,1429,311,1948]" pageId="4" pageNumber="224">
<taxonomicName id="4C464D45FF81232DFCD4FC1BFBDA9B84" box="[864,1090,928,952]" class="Arachnida" family="Eriophyidae" genus="Calacarus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="4" pageNumber="224" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="citrifolii">
<emphasis id="B932EAD4FF81232DFCD4FC1BFBDA9B84" bold="true" box="[864,1090,928,952]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="224">Calacarus citrifolii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is recorded for the Afrotropical region (
<collectingCountry id="F3517656FF81232DFC73FC78FBB89BE7" box="[967,1056,963,987]" name="Angola" pageId="4" pageNumber="224">Angola</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="F3517656FF81232DFB9AFC7FFBE49BE0" box="[1070,1148,964,988]" name="Kenya" pageId="4" pageNumber="224">Kenya</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="F3517656FF81232DFB3EFC78FAB09BE7" box="[1162,1320,963,987]" name="Mozambique" pageId="4" pageNumber="224">Mozambique</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="F3517656FF81232DFA81FC78FA089BE7" box="[1333,1424,963,987]" name="Nigeria" pageId="4" pageNumber="224">Nigeria</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="F3517656FF81232DFC8EFC5DFC4F9BC2" box="[826,983,998,1022]" name="South Africa" pageId="4" pageNumber="224">South Africa</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="F3517656FF81232DFC5EFC5DFBDC9BC2" box="[1002,1092,998,1022]" name="Zambia" pageId="4" pageNumber="224">Zambia</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry id="F3517656FF81232DFB38FC5DFA979BC2" box="[1164,1295,998,1022]" name="Zimbabwe" pageId="4" pageNumber="224">Zimbabwe</collectingCountry>
). The citrus blotch mite transmits a serious citrus disease, known as &quot;concentric ring blotch&quot;, caused by its toxic saliva. However, high levels of attack are not always associated with the disease (
<bibRefCitation id="EFD74B37FF81232DFA9CFBC8FC619C92" author="Rossouw D. J. &amp; Smith A. J." pageId="4" pageNumber="224" pagination="7" refId="ref16430" refString="Rossouw D. J., Smith A. J. 1963 - The relation of Calacarus citrifolii Keifer to concentric ring blotch of citrus - S. Afric. Citrus J., 354: 7, 9." type="journal article" year="1963">Rossouw and Smith, 1963</bibRefCitation>
) that affects the young tissues and during periods of strong growth damages young leaves, shoots, branches and fruits; mature leaves and shoots appear to be exempt.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF936C6FF81232DFCD4FA92FB429F35" blockId="4.[826,1429,311,1948]" pageId="4" pageNumber="224">
The natural enemies of the 
<taxonomicName id="4C464D45FF81232DFB10FA92FAAD9D7D" authorityName="Nalepa" authorityYear="1898" box="[1188,1333,1321,1345]" class="Arachnida" family="Eriophyidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="4" pageNumber="224" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Eriophyidae</taxonomicName>
include pathogens (viruses, fungi such as the 
<taxonomicName id="4C464D45FF81232DFA96FAF7FC1D9DBB" class="Sordariomycetes" family="Clavicipitaceae" kingdom="Fungi" order="Hypocreales" pageId="4" pageNumber="224" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="family">Clavicipitaceae</taxonomicName>
, Exobasidiomycetidae, 
<taxonomicName id="4C464D45FF81232DFB2CFAD4FA119DBB" authorityName="Lindau" authorityYear="1897" box="[1176,1417,1391,1415]" class="Dothideomycetes" family="Mycosphaerellaceae" kingdom="Fungi" order="Capnodiales" pageId="4" pageNumber="224" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="family">Mycosphaerellaceae</taxonomicName>
), molluscs (
<taxonomicName id="4C464D45FF81232DFC01FA29FBD39D96" authorityName="Martens" authorityYear="1860" box="[949,1099,1426,1450]" class="Gastropoda" family="Orthalicidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="4" pageNumber="224" phylum="Mollusca" rank="family">Orthalicidae</taxonomicName>
), mites (
<taxonomicName id="4C464D45FF81232DFB03FA29FA809D96" authorityName="Voigts &amp; Oudemans" authorityYear="1905" box="[1207,1304,1426,1450]" class="Arachnida" family="Ascidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mesostigmata" pageId="4" pageNumber="224" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Ascidae</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C464D45FF81232DFA9DFA29FCFE9DF1" authorityName="W.E.Leach" authorityYear="1815" class="Arachnida" family="Cheyletidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="4" pageNumber="224" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Cheyletidae</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C464D45FF81232DFCC0FA0EFB969DF1" authorityName="A.Berlese" authorityYear="1916" box="[884,1038,1461,1485]" class="Arachnida" family="Phytoseiidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mesostigmata" pageId="4" pageNumber="224" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Phytoseiidae</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C464D45FF81232DFBAFFA0EFB369DF1" authorityName="Oudemans" authorityYear="1931" box="[1051,1198,1461,1485]" class="Arachnida" family="Stigmaeidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="4" pageNumber="224" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Stigmaeidae</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C464D45FF81232DFB0FFA0EFAB29DF1" authorityName="P.Kramer" authorityYear="1877" box="[1211,1322,1461,1485]" class="Arachnida" family="Tydeidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="4" pageNumber="224" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Tydeidae</taxonomicName>
), and insects (
<taxonomicName id="4C464D45FF81232DFC37FA62FBA09DCD" box="[899,1080,1497,1521]" class="Insecta" family="Cecidomyiidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="224" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Cecidomyiidae</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C464D45FF81232DFBF3FA62FB709DCD" authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1807" box="[1095,1256,1497,1521]" class="Insecta" family="Coccinellidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="224" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Coccinellidae</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C464D45FF81232DFB43FA62FCFE9E28" class="Insecta" family="Coniopterigidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="224" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Coniopterigidae</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C464D45FF81232DFCC3FA47FC699E28" box="[887,1009,1532,1556]" class="Insecta" family="Psychidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="224" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Psychidae</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C464D45FF81232DFBB5FA47FBEE9E28" authorityName="Stevens" authorityYear="1829" box="[1025,1142,1532,1556]" class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="224" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Thripidae</taxonomicName>
) (
<bibRefCitation id="EFD74B37FF81232DFB24FA47FAA29E28" author="Vacante V." box="[1168,1338,1532,1556]" pageId="4" pageNumber="224" refId="ref17129" refString="Vacante V. 2010 - Citrus Mites - Wallingford: CABI Publishing. pp. 378." type="book" year="2010">Vacante, 2010</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName id="4C464D45FF81232DFAEEFA47FB9C9E0B" baseAuthorityName="Ashmead" baseAuthorityYear="1879" class="Arachnida" family="Eriophyidae" genus="Phyllocoptruta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="4" pageNumber="224" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="oleivora">
<emphasis id="B932EAD4FF81232DFAEEFA47FB9C9E0B" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="224">Phyllocoptruta oleivora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the most studied species, both because of its wide geographical distribution and severe damage. In general, natural enemies do not provide an appreciable measure of control, except in special cases, like the Phytoseiid 
<taxonomicName id="4C464D45FF81232DFB67F917FC6D9EDA" authority="(Womersley)" baseAuthorityName="Womersley" baseAuthorityYear="1954" class="Arachnida" family="Phytoseiidae" genus="Euseius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mesostigmata" pageId="4" pageNumber="224" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="victoriensis">
<emphasis id="B932EAD4FF81232DFB67F917FCCE9EDA" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="224">Euseius victoriensis</emphasis>
(Womersley)
</taxonomicName>
that provides a good control of 
<taxonomicName id="4C464D45FF81232DFA34F974FC0F9F35" class="Arachnida" family="Eriophyidae" genus="Tegolophus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="4" pageNumber="224" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="australis">
<emphasis id="B932EAD4FF81232DFA34F974FC0F9F35" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="224">T. australis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFD74B37FF81232DFC11F94AFB569F35" author="Smith D. &amp; Papacek D. F." box="[933,1230,1777,1801]" pageId="4" pageNumber="224" pagination="195 - 217" refId="ref16669" refString="Smith D., Papacek D. F. 1991 - Studies on the predatory mite Amblyseius victoriensis (Acarina: Phytoseiidae) in citrus orchards in south-east Queensland: control of Tegolophus australis and Phyllocoptruta oleivora (Acarina: Eriophyidae), effect of pesticides, alternative host plants and augmentative release - Exp. Appl. Acarol., 12: 195 - 217." type="journal article" year="1991">
<collectingRegion id="4982F824FF81232DFC11F94AFC739F35" box="[933,1003,1777,1801]" country="Bermuda" name="Smith's" pageId="4" pageNumber="224">Smith</collectingRegion>
and Papacek, 1991
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF936C6FF81232CFCD4F8A0FDAA9A1D" blockId="4.[826,1429,311,1948]" lastBlockId="5.[159,762,311,545]" lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="225" pageId="4" pageNumber="224">
Citrus rust mites control is usually based on chemical means (
<bibRefCitation id="EFD74B37FF81232DFBB0F884FB3E9F6B" author="Vacante V." box="[1028,1190,1855,1879]" pageId="4" pageNumber="224" refId="ref17129" refString="Vacante V. 2010 - Citrus Mites - Wallingford: CABI Publishing. pp. 378." type="book" year="2010">Vacante, 2010</bibRefCitation>
) and the main innovations consist basically on the definition of thresholds and introduction of new methods of sampling and monitoring of populations (
<bibRefCitation id="EFD74B37FF80232CFDAFFE8CFD3A9973" author="Allen J. C." box="[539,674,311,335]" pageId="5" pageNumber="225" pagination="171 - 176" refId="ref10450" refString="Allen J. C. 1981 - The citrus rust mite game: a simulation model of pest losses - Environ. Entomol., 10: 171 - 176." type="journal article" year="1981">Allen, 1981</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFD74B37FF80232CFD1BFE8CFEE5994E" author="Nascimento A. S. do &amp; Caldas R. C. &amp; Silva L. M. S. da" pageId="5" pageNumber="225" pagination="157 - 162" refId="ref15230" refString="Nascimento A. S. do, Caldas R. C., Silva L. M. S. da 1982 - Amostragem do acaro da ferrugem Phyllocoptruta oleivora (Ashmead, 1879) (Acari: Eriophyidae) - Ann. Soc. Entomol. Bras., 11: 157 - 162." type="journal article" year="1982">
Nascimento 
<emphasis id="B932EAD4FF80232CFF42FEE0FEB1994E" box="[246,297,346,370]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="225">et al</emphasis>
., 1982
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFD74B37FF80232CFE25FEE1FD1C994E" author="Oliveira C. A. L. de &amp; Mauro A. O. &amp; Kronka S. N." box="[401,644,346,370]" pageId="5" pageNumber="225" pagination="101 - 114" refId="ref15438" refString="Oliveira C. A. L. de, Mauro A. O., Kronka S. N. 1982 - Comparacao de metodos para estimativas da populacao do acaro Phyllocoptruta oleivora (Ashmead, 1879) na cultura do citrus - Ann. Soc. Entomol. Bras., 11: 101 - 114." type="journal article" year="1982">
Oliveira 
<emphasis id="B932EAD4FF80232CFE49FEE0FDA8994E" box="[509,560,346,370]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="225">et al</emphasis>
., 1982
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFD74B37FF80232CFD23FEE1FF4F99A9" author="Manzur B. E." pageId="5" pageNumber="225" pagination="55 - 63" refId="ref14176" refString="Manzur B. E. 1989 - Plan de muestreo secuencial para acaro del tostado Phyllocoptruta oleivora (Ashm.) (Acari: Eriophyidae), en citricos - Revista de Information - CIRPON, 7 (1 - 43): 55 - 63." type="journal article" year="1989">Manzur, 1989</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFD74B37FF80232CFF51FEC6FE2699A9" author="Rogers J. S. &amp; McCoy C. W. &amp; Manners M. M." box="[229,446,381,405]" pageId="5" pageNumber="225" pagination="1507 - 1512" refId="ref16336" refString="Rogers J. S., McCoy C. W., Manners M. M. 1994 - Standardized visual comparison keys for rapid estimations of citrus rust mite (Acari: Eriophyidae) populations - J. Econ. Entomol., 87: 1507 - 1512." type="journal article" year="1994">
Rogers 
<emphasis id="B932EAD4FF80232CFEF4FEC5FEF799A9" box="[320,367,381,405]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="225">et al</emphasis>
., 1994
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFD74B37FF80232CFE78FEC6FD2099A9" author="Childers C. C. &amp; McCoy C. W. &amp; Nigg H. N. &amp; Stansly P. A. &amp; Rogers, M. E." box="[460,696,381,405]" pageId="5" pageNumber="225" refId="ref11785" refString="Childers C. C., McCoy C. W., Nigg H. N., Stansly P. A., Rogers, M. E. 2007 - 2007 Florida Citrus Pest Management Guide: Rust Mites, Spider Mites, and Other Phytophagous Mites - ENY- 603, UF, University of Florida, IFAS Extension, pp. 7." type="journal volume" year="2007">
Childers 
<emphasis id="B932EAD4FF80232CFD8EFEC5FDF199A9" box="[570,617,381,405]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="225">et al</emphasis>
., 2007
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFD74B37FF80232CFD73FEC6FEBB9984" author="Hall D. G. &amp; Childers C. C. &amp; Eger J. E." pageId="5" pageNumber="225" pagination="233 - 240" refId="ref13225" refString="Hall D. G., Childers C. C., Eger J. E. 2007 - Binomial sampling to estimate citrus rust mite (Acari: Eriophyidae) densities on orange fruit - J. Econ. Entomol., 100: 233 - 240." type="journal article" year="2007">
Hall 
<emphasis id="B932EAD4FF80232CFF2BFE1AFF489984" box="[159,208,416,440]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="225">et al</emphasis>
., 2007
</bibRefCitation>
), which are aimed at rationalizing the use of acaricides within integrated pest management (IPM) programs (
<bibRefCitation id="EFD74B37FF80232CFE07FE5DFDDC99C2" author="Rosen D." box="[435,580,486,510]" pageId="5" pageNumber="225" pagination="521 - 530" refId="ref16386" refString="Rosen D. 1986 - Methodologies and strategies of pest control in citriculture - In: Cavalloro R., Di Martino E. (Eds). Integrated pest control in citrus-groves. Rotterdam: Balkema. pp. 521 - 530." type="book chapter" year="1986">Rosen, 1986</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFD74B37FF80232CFDE6FE5CFD6E99C2" author="Vacante V." box="[594,758,486,510]" pageId="5" pageNumber="225" pagination="423 - 431" refId="ref17028" refString="Vacante V. 1986 - Influence of white mineral oil treatments on the population dynamics of some mites in a lemon orchard in Eastern Sicily - In: Cavalloro R., Di Martino E. (Eds). Integrated pest control in citrusgroves. Rotterdam: Balkema. pp. 423 - 431." type="book chapter" year="1986">Vacante, 1986</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFD74B37FF80232CFF2BFDB2FEAE9A1D" author="McCoy C. W." box="[159,310,521,545]" pageId="5" pageNumber="225" pagination="513 - 526" refId="ref14365" refString="McCoy C. W. 1996 - Stylar Feeding Injury and Control of Eriophyoid Mites in Citrus - In: Lindquist E. E., Sabelis M. W., Bruin J. (Eds). Eriophyoid Mites-Their Biology, Natural Enemies and Control. Amsterdam: Elsevier Science Publ. Vol. 6. pp. 513 - 526." type="journal article" year="1996">McCoy, 1996</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFD74B37FF80232CFEF5FDB2FDBF9A1D" author="Childers C. C. &amp; McCoy C. W. &amp; Nigg H. N. &amp; Stansly P. A. &amp; Rogers, M. E." box="[321,551,521,545]" pageId="5" pageNumber="225" refId="ref11785" refString="Childers C. C., McCoy C. W., Nigg H. N., Stansly P. A., Rogers, M. E. 2007 - 2007 Florida Citrus Pest Management Guide: Rust Mites, Spider Mites, and Other Phytophagous Mites - ENY- 603, UF, University of Florida, IFAS Extension, pp. 7." type="journal volume" year="2007">
Childers 
<emphasis id="B932EAD4FF80232CFE18FDB1FE409A1D" box="[428,472,521,545]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="225">et al</emphasis>
., 2007
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
